  <h3>“Ultras” and “football hooliganism”</h3>

  <p>Football, or in American English soccer, is the most popular and the most spectacular sport on the planet. Soccer fans are also connected with the culture of «ultras» and football hooliganism. These may be different phenomena, but are subject to mutual influences. Ultras and football hooliganism are widespread throughout the whole world, but they trace their beginnings from Europe.</p>
  <p>The culture of ultras arrived from Italy. The term «ultras» was first used in 1969 in the names of organized groups of fans: fans of the club «Sampdoria,» who called themselves ultras Tito Cucchiaroni, and fans of the club «Torino,» who called themselves ultras Granata. The «ultras» movement became associated with a particular style of being a fan--with chants, fireworks, banners and flash-mobs. The ultras culture transformed the emotional spectatorship of a game into a mass organized support of a team. Ultras group the most active fans. With participants’ contributions the ultras prepare banners and travel together to guest matches.</p>
  <p>The first case of large-scale fighting among fans, called «football hooliganism,» occurred in England in 1955 between fans of two Liverpool teams, Everton and Liverpool.  Football hooliganism was marked by radicalism and violence. Inspired by extremist ideas either leftist or rightist, it was often connected with racism. Football hooligans express loyalty to their team in fights—called makhachy—with the fans from opposing teams.</p>
  <p>Although the ultras limit themselves from football hooliganism, it is often difficult to draw a line between these two phenomena. And so some countries, like England, see the ultras as a threat in stadiums and take severe legal restrictions: it is forbidden to bring large banners, flags and pyrotechnics into the stadium,  nor is it permitted to stand during the match.</p>
    
  <h4>Right and Left of “Ultras” in Ukraine</h4>
